Anonymous Wed 11 Apr 2018 00:06:24 No.15100167 Report

>Everyone dumped the comic after that.

Well, I certainly did. Not immediately, but it's like the veil on the entire writing process was liften in one fell swoop. I thought Endtown was pretty brilliant before that. Everything about the comic worked, despite everything about it saying it shouldn't. It's an edgy, hyperviolent, post-apocalyptic comic with anthropomorphic animal people in a newspaper comic style, with occasional newspaper comic style humour. I mean, the bear dude looks a lot like a popular comic character from my country.

But somehow Aaron turned that animal people thing into almost stomach-turning body horror. The whimsical town into a mad prison. The simple, understated artstyle into the bleakest wasteland in fiction. It just... worked. And it was an emotional rollercoaster.

But with the Holly arc, it all went to shit. The first sign was his design choice for the lizards. He just started drawing them with those weird, long legs. That's not something an artist who plans ahead does. And him just deciding that Kirbee should not only be a main character, but that she and Wally had to be close really ruined Wally and Holly's character arcs. And why? Because he liked Kirbee. Seeing his earlier comics, it seems more clear. They're really bad, simply put. They're not funny, but they don't have Endtown's hard edge, either. Almost unbelievable they're all the same characters, really.

So yeah, a disappointing flashback arc that promised something big, but ended up being an excuse to write out Holly in favour of Kirbee. It's just such a normie, crappy webcomic thing to do, compared to the earlier, rather unflinching writing. I suppose there were signs with whatshisface, the self insert character. I could deal with Flask's Deus Ex Machina end, because the character arc ended appropriately.

I'm just disappointed that such an unique comic would go to pieces this way. I think Aaron is kind of crazy, but that crazy really worked for a long time.
